17-07-14 19:06:01'),(132,'Defenses and Justifications',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',0,0,'2017-07-14 19:06:01'),(133,'Actus Reus / Mens Rea / Concurrence','\r\nNegative Action in Actus Reus\r\nLegal Duty to act\r\nKnowledge of facts\r\nIs it reasonable for them to perform',NULL,NULL,'criminal',125,0,'2017-07-14 19:06:57'),(134,'Accomplice Liability','An accomplice is one who actively aids and assists in the commission of a crime.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',125,0,'2017-07-14 19:06:57'),(135,'Intent',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',134,0,'2017-07-14 19:07:17'),(136,'Knowledge',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',134,0,'2017-07-14 19:07:17'),(137,'Active Assistance',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',134,0,'2017-07-14 19:08:15'),(138,'Vicarious Liability',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',125,0,'2017-07-14 19:08:30'),(139,'Solicitation','Intent to induce another to commit a crime.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',126,0,'2017-07-14 19:09:18'),(140,'Attempt',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',126,0,'2017-07-14 19:09:18'),(141,'Conspiracy','Agreement between two or more persons to commit an unlawful act.\r\n\r\nUnder a majority jurisdiction, an overt act is required.','Beth drove Al to the Friendly Market. Here if Beth know that Al is doing something wrong, Beth can be considered as conspirator.',NULL,'criminal',126,0,'2017-07-14 19:09:30'),(142,'Homicide','Killing of one human being by another human being.\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',127,0,'2017-07-14 19:10:08'),(143,'Non-Homicide',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',127,0,'2017-07-14 19:10:08'),(144,'IRAC Homicide',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',142,0,'2017-07-14 19:11:58'),(145,'Causation',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',142,0,'2017-07-14 19:11:58'),(146,'Murder','Murder is a homicide committed with malice aforethought.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',142,0,'2017-07-14 19:12:34'),(147,'First Degree Murder','First degree murder is murder committed by poison; torture; lying in wait; or other willful, deliberate and premeditated means; or murder that results from application of the Felony Murder Rule.\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:12:34'),(148,'Second Degree Murder','Second degree murder is all murders which are not first degree murder, in other words, those homicides committed with malice aforethought but which do not meet the requirements for murder in the first degree.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:13:03'),(149,'Justification','A. Defenses\r\n	i. Self Defense\r\n	ii. Defense of Others\r\n	iii. Defense of Property\r\n	iv. Prevention of Crime\r\n	v. Public Authority\r\n	vi. Domestic Authority\r\n	vii. Necessity\r\nB. Justifications (to negate mens rea)\r\n	i. Mistake of law\r\n	ii. Mistake of fact\r\n	iii. Consent\r\n	iv. Duress\r\n	v. Entrapment\r\n\r\nPrevention of Crime\r\nCrime prevention is allowed when you see the victim engaged in the commission of an inherently dangerous felony and the felon was fleeing the scene.\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:13:03'),(150,'Excuse (3 i\'s)','Excuses\r\n	i. Infancy\r\n	ii. Intoxication\r\n	iii. Insanity\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:13:36'),(151,'Mitigation',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:13:36'),(152,'Voluntary Manslaughter','Voluntary Manslaughter is a murder which, because of mitigating circumstances, is treated as less heinous than first or second degree murder.\r\n\r\nHeat of Passion: if defendant can prove\r\nadequate provocation to lead a reasonable person to lose his normal self-control,\r\nthe defendant actually lost his self-control, and \r\nthere was not enough time for the defendant to cool off between the provocation and the murder.\r\n\r\nImperfect Self Defense\r\n    retreat if safe\r\n    dont have to retreat, use self defense\r\n\r\nMistaken Justification\r\n\r\nCoercion\r\nThe practice of persuading someone to do something by using force or threats.\r\n\r\nDiminished Capacity\r\nUnder the Diminished Capacity Test, also known as the Wells-Gorshin Rule, evidence of mental infirmity not amounting to insanity is admissible and should be considered on questions of premeditation, deliberation, and malice, although diminished capacity is not a complete defense.\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',146,0,'2017-07-14 19:13:55'),(153,'Assault','Assault is either the substantial step towards the perpetration of an intended battery or the intentional placing of another in reasonable apprehension of an imminent harmful application of force.','Substantial Step\r\n\r\nB raised his arm to swing to punch G. The raising and swinging of his arm is a substantial step towards the perpetration of the subsequent hitting.\r\nB is guilty of this type of assault, but it will merge with the subsequent battery.\r\n\r\nReasonable Apprehension\r\n\r\nSince G was facing B, she would have been able to see him raise his arm to swing at her. Given that she had just threatened to call the police, G could have anticipated a violent response and would have been in reasonable apprehension when she saw him raise his arm.\r\nB is guilty of this type of assault.',NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:17:23'),(154,'Battery','The unlawful application of force to another\'s person','B knocked G out. Punching is an application of force and it was applied to G, another person. B did not have a right to do so; thus it was unlawful.',NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:17:35'),(155,'False Imprisonment',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:17:47'),(156,'Kidnapping','Kidnapping is the movement of a person against his will from one place to another.','B knocked G out and made her unconscious. Since G was unconscious and could not escape, she was confined. B then put her in the car and took her to F\'s house. This is movement and asportation of G.\r\n\r\nB is guilty of kidnapping',NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:17:53'),(157,'Mayhem',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:18:04'),(158,'Rape',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',143,0,'2017-07-15 13:18:12'),(159,'Burglary',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',128,0,'2017-07-15 13:18:47'),(160,'Arson','The malicious burning of the dwelling house of another.\r\n\r\nModern Law\r\nThe malicious burning of any structure.\r\n\r\n','Bob pushed Fred, causing him to knock over a lamp and start a fire. Bob will argue that\r\nhe did not intend for the house to catch fire, and therefore his action was not malicious.\r\nThe State will argue that he should have reasonably expected and known that pushing\r\nFred would have caused the fire. Since the facts indicate the house began to burn, it is\r\nlikely that at least charring to the structure had occurred.\r\n\r\nIf the court finds that Bob should have known pushing Bob would cause a fire, then he will\r\nbe guilty of common law arson. If the court finds he did not know, then he will not be found\r\nto be malicious and will not be guilty.\r\n',NULL,'criminal',128,0,'2017-07-15 13:18:55'),(161,'Common Law','Breaking and entering the dwelling house of another, at night, with the specific intent to commit a felony therein.\r\n','Breaking and entering\r\nB went to F\'s house. Since the door was locked, he broke it. This is sufficient for a breaking. B then entered.\r\n\r\nDwelling of another\r\nFacts indicate that this was F\'s house. A dwelling\r\n\r\nNighttime\r\nThe facts do not indicate whether this event happens at night or not. Night is defined as the period between sunset and sunrise. Since the fact pattern began in the morning, it is likely still the daytime.\r\n\r\nSpecific Intent to Commit a Felony\r\nB intended to hide unconscious Gina in F\'s house. As discussed supra, this is a kidnapping and a felony sufficient enough for this element.\r\n       \r\nSince it is likely not the nighttime, B is not guilty of common law burglary. However, if it is the nighttime, then he would be guilty.',NULL,'criminal',159,0,'2017-07-15 13:19:09'),(162,'Statutory',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',159,0,'2017-07-15 13:25:45'),(163,'Larceny & Larceny by Trick','Trespassory taking and carrying away the personal property of another without consent, with specific intent to permanently deprive.\r\n\r\nLarceny by trick is a form of larceny in which the taking of the personal property of another was done with the owners consent; however, the consent was obtained by deceit or fraud.\r\n\r\n','trespassory taking, without consent, carrying away, permanently deprive, has to be proved here.\r\n\r\nBob picked up a valuable necklace that was on the counter at the bank. The taking was\r\ntrespassory because it did not belong to Bob and he did not have permission to take it.\r\nHe put it in his pocket; this is sufficient movement to constitute as a carrying away. The\r\nproperty did not belong to Bob, so it was that of another\'s. Bob will argue that he did not\r\nintend to keep it, especially since he put the necklace back. The State will argue that\r\nsince the facts indicate that Bob was an \"underpaid teller\" it is likely that Bob specifically\r\nmeant to take it and deprive the owner thereof so he could have the value. Additionally,\r\nonly after he was caught did he put it back.\r\n\r\nBob is guilty of larceny.',NULL,'criminal',129,0,'2017-07-15 13:26:38'),(164,'False Pretenses','Obtaining property by false pretenses is the obtaining of title to the property of another through a false representation of fact with the intent to defraud.\r\n',NULL,NULL,'criminal',129,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:14'),(165,'Embezzlement','Embezzlement is the fraudulent taking of the personal property of another by one to whom possession has been entrusted.\r\n','When Fred gave Bob a roll of quarters and asked for a ten-dollar bill, Bob told Fred that\r\nhe would secretly give him $100. Bob enticed Fred to take the $100, instead of the $10\r\nthat he was owed, therefore depriving the bank (the owner) of the additional $90. Since\r\nBob was a bank teller, he was rightfully entrusted with the money that he gave to Fred,\r\nbut he converted the remaining $90 for purposes that were inconsistent with the Bank\'s\r\nownership.',NULL,'criminal',129,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:23'),(166,'Robbery','Robbery is the trespassory taking and carrying away the personal property of another with the intent to permanently deprive the owner thereof by force, fear or intimidation.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',129,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:26'),(167,'Receiving Stolen Property','Receiving stolen property is the acquisition of stolen property with knowledge at the time of receipt that it was stolen, when done with intent to deprive the owner of his or her property.',NULL,NULL,'criminal',129,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:38'),(168,'Forgery',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',130,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:54'),(169,'Uttering',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',130,0,'2017-07-15 13:30:57'),(170,'Extortion','Extortion is the unlawful obtaining of property from another through coercion, usually involving a threat to perform an illegal act in the future.\r\n','Alma intends to use the confidential documents to threaten Ed with embarrassment, resulting in him paying her money. It is irrelevant that she believes he owes her overtime pay because she is still guilty of the attempt to extort payment by threat of embarrassment. Causation is met because she would not have taken the substantial step toward threatening Ed with embarrassment to get him to give her money if she hadn\'t entered his office with the intent to steal the documents for this purpose.',NULL,'criminal',130,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:00'),(171,'Misprison',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:16'),(172,'Compounding',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:21'),(173,'Riot',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:23'),(174,'Rout',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:25'),(175,'Unlawful Assembly',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:32'),(176,'Malicious Mischief',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:31:42'),(177,'Breach of Peace',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',131,0,'2017-07-15 13:32:54'),(178,'Defenses',NULL,NULL,NULL,'criminal',132,0,'2017-07-15 13:33:30'),(179,'Justification',NULL